<p>Previous uses of social-learning behavioural models to study epidemics have focused on vaccination and treatment games, often using mean-field approximations [
 <xref rid="RSOS201095C24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>–
 <xref rid="RSOS201095C27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>]. We use the mean-field approximation technique to solve our model's system of equations, as it is stochastic in nature. We build upon the well-known susceptible–exposed–infected–recovered (SEIR) compartmental model of epidemic dynamics to calculate the numbers of quarantined and infected individuals (
 <italic>Q</italic>(
 <italic>t</italic>) and 
 <italic>I</italic>
 <sup>tot</sup>(
 <italic>t</italic>)). We add terms for quarantined and hospitalized individuals to produce a SEQIHR (susceptible–exposed–quarantined–infected–hospitalized–recovered) compartmental model. The model is expressed by the following set of differential equations, whose relationships are diagrammed in 
